<TITLE> Bangladesh hosts AFC Challenge Cup qualifiers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 28 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh have been drawn in Group A along with Myanmar, Cambodia and Macau or Mongolia in the AFC Challenge Cup qualifying round. The draw for 16 teams was an interesting scene at the headquarters of the Asian Football Confederation in Kuala Lumpur in Malaysia on Wednesday. Bangladesh, Maldives, Nepal and Sri Lanka will host the Group matches in April after two play-off matches between Macau and Mongolia in March as the AFC decided to hold play-off after 17 teams sought entry in the qualifiers. Bangladesh Football Federation member Anwarul Haq Helal confirmed that Bangladesh would host the AFC Challenge Cup qualifiers. As many as 16 nations, split into four groups, will play the robin-round league matches and top team from each group and the best runners-up will qualify for the eight-team final round. Holders India, runners-up Tajikistan and third-placed DPR Korea are getting the direct entries, according to the AFC. Hosts Nepal have been drawn in tough Group C along with Afghanistan, Kyrgyzstan and Palestine while Group B includes Turkmenistan, the Philippines, Bhutan and hosts Maldives. Hosts Sri Lanka, Pakistan, Chinese Taipei and Brunei Darussalam have been pooled in Group D. Group A: Myanmar, Cambodia, Bangladesh, Macau/Mongolia Group B: Turkmenistan, The Philippines, Bhutan, Maldives Group C: Nepal, Afghanistan, Kyrgyzstan, Palestine Group D: Sri Lanka, Pakistan, Chinese Taipei, Brunei Darussalam
